# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: afghanistan-a-cricket-team
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:afghanistan-a-cricket-team/2013-acc-emerging-teams-cup] The **2013 ACC Emerging Teams Cup** was the first edition of the ACC Emerging Teams Asia Cup was held in Singapore.
[src:afghanistan-a-cricket-team/2013-acc-emerging-teams-cup] Eight teams participated in the tournament, comprising four under-23 teams from Test nations and four top associate teams from Asia.
[src:afghanistan-a-cricket-team/2017-acc-emerging-teams-asia-cup] The **2017 ACC Emerging Teams Asia Cup** was the second edition of the ACC Emerging Teams Asia Cup held in Bangladesh.
[src:afghanistan-a-cricket-team/2017-acc-emerging-teams-asia-cup] Eight teams participated in the tournament including four under-23 age level teams of Test nations and four top associate teams from Asia.This Competition was organized by ACC (Asian Cricket Council).
[src:afghanistan-a-cricket-team/2017-south-africa-a-team-tri-series] The **2017 South Africa A Team Tri-Series** was a cricket tournament that took place in South Africa in July and August 2017.
[src:afghanistan-a-cricket-team/2017-south-africa-a-team-tri-series] It was a tri-nation series between South Africa A, Afghanistan A and India A.
[src:afghanistan-a-cricket-team/2017-south-africa-a-team-tri-series] The one-day matches were played as List A fixtures.
[src:afghanistan-a-cricket-team/2017-south-africa-a-team-tri-series] Following the List A fixtures, South Africa A and India A played two four-day games with first-class status, also called unofficial Tests.
[src:afghanistan-a-cricket-team/2017-south-africa-a-team-tri-series] Originally, Australia A were scheduled to play in the series, but they withdrew in early July following an ongoing pay dispute with Cricket Australia.
[src:afghanistan-a-cricket-team/2017-south-africa-a-team-tri-series] Later that month, Afghanistan A was named their replacement after the national team had been awarded test match status the previous month.
[src:afghanistan-a-cricket-team/2017-south-africa-a-team-tri-series] India A won the tri-series, beating South Africa A by 7 wickets in the competition's final.
[src:afghanistan-a-cricket-team/2017-south-africa-a-team-tri-series] The first-class series was drawn 1–1, with South Africa A winning the first match and India A winning the second.
[src:afghanistan-a-cricket-team/2017-south-africa-a-team-tri-series] Ravikumar Samarth replaced Abhinav Mukund following the former's selection to the India squad for the Sri Lanka tour.
[src:afghanistan-a-cricket-team/2018-acc-emerging-teams-asia-cup] The **2018 ACC Emerging Teams Asia Cup** was the third edition of the ACC Emerging Teams Asia Cup held in Karachi, Pakistan and Colombo, Sri Lanka.
[src:afghanistan-a-cricket-team/2018-acc-emerging-teams-asia-cup] Eight teams participated in the tournament including five under-23 age level teams of Test nations and top three teams from the 2018 Asia Cup Qualifier.
[src:afghanistan-a-cricket-team/2018-acc-emerging-teams-asia-cup] This tournament was organized by the Asian Cricket Council (ACC).
[src:afghanistan-a-cricket-team/2018-acc-emerging-teams-asia-cup] Initially, Pakistan was the sole host for the tournament but India and BCCI refused to send Indian players to Pakistan.
[src:afghanistan-a-cricket-team/2018-acc-emerging-teams-asia-cup] Following the increasing political tensions between India and Pakistan, the ACC announced that Sri Lanka would be the co-host whilst India's matches and knockout stage will be played there.
[src:afghanistan-a-cricket-team/2018-acc-emerging-teams-asia-cup] The U-23 teams from India, Bangladesh, Sri Lanka and Pakistan qualified for the semi-finals.
[src:afghanistan-a-cricket-team/2018-acc-emerging-teams-asia-cup] Sri Lanka's U-23 defeated India U-23 by 3 runs in the final to win the tournament.
[src:afghanistan-a-cricket-team/2019-acc-emerging-teams-asia-cup] The **2019 ACC Emerging Teams Asia Cup** was the fourth edition of the ACC Emerging Teams Asia Cup held in Bangladesh between 14 and 23 November 2019.
[src:afghanistan-a-cricket-team/2019-acc-emerging-teams-asia-cup] Eight teams participated in the tournament, including five under-23 age level teams of Test nations and the top three teams from the 2018 Asia Cup Qualifier.
[src:afghanistan-a-cricket-team/2019-acc-emerging-teams-asia-cup] The tournament was organized by the Asian Cricket Council (ACC).
[src:afghanistan-a-cricket-team/2019-acc-emerging-teams-asia-cup] Nepal replaced the United Arab Emirates, after they pulled out due to an unknown reason.
[src:afghanistan-a-cricket-team/2019-acc-emerging-teams-asia-cup] Nepal qualified by virtue of being fourth in the Asia Cup qualifier.
[src:afghanistan-a-cricket-team/2019-acc-emerging-teams-asia-cup] The two finalists, Pakistan and Bangladesh, remained undefeated until reaching the final.
[src:afghanistan-a-cricket-team/2019-acc-emerging-teams-asia-cup] Pakistan won the tournament, beating Bangladesh by 77 runs in the final.
[src:afghanistan-a-cricket-team/2019-acc-emerging-teams-asia-cup] Prior to the start of the tournament, India's Kamlesh Nagarkoti and Arshdeep Singh were ruled out of the tournament and were replaced by Aditya Thakare and Shivam Mavi respectively.
[src:afghanistan-a-cricket-team/2023-acc-emerging-teams-asia-cup] The **2023 ACC Emerging Teams Asia Cup** was the fifth edition of the ACC Emerging Teams Asia Cup.
[src:afghanistan-a-cricket-team/2023-acc-emerging-teams-asia-cup] It took place from 13 to 23 July 2023 in Sri Lanka.
[src:afghanistan-a-cricket-team/2023-acc-emerging-teams-asia-cup] The tournament featured a total of eight teams, which included five 'A' teams from the full members of the Asian Cricket Council; and the top three teams from the 2023 ACC Men's Premier Cup.
[src:afghanistan-a-cricket-team/2023-acc-emerging-teams-asia-cup] The 'A' teams from UAE, Oman, and the Nepal national cricket team also participated.
[src:afghanistan-a-cricket-team/2023-acc-emerging-teams-asia-cup] Pakistan A won the tournament, defeating India A by 128 runs in the final.
[src:afghanistan-a-cricket-team/2023-acc-emerging-teams-asia-cup] In January 2023, the Asian Cricket Council (ACC) announced the pathway structure and calendar for 2023 and 2024, where they confirmed the dates and format of the tournament.
[src:afghanistan-a-cricket-team/2023-acc-emerging-teams-asia-cup] They later announced the fixtures of the tournament on the first week of July.
[src:afghanistan-a-cricket-team/2023-acc-emerging-teams-asia-cup] Prior to the start of the tournament, Nepal's Aarif Sheikh was ruled out of the tournament and was replaced by Pawan Sarraf.
[src:afghanistan-a-cricket-team/2023-acc-emerging-teams-asia-cup] Fixtures of the tournament was announced by ACC on 6 July 2023.
[src:afghanistan-a-cricket-team/2023-acc-emerging-teams-asia-cup] Star Sports Network broadcast in Indian Subcontinent.
[src:afghanistan-a-cricket-team/2024-acc-emerging-teams-asia-cup] The **2024 ACC Emerging Teams Asia Cup** was the sixth edition of the ACC Emerging Teams Asia Cup that was played in October 2024 in Muscat, Oman.
[src:afghanistan-a-cricket-team/2024-acc-emerging-teams-asia-cup] Eight teams competed in the tournament, including 'A' teams i.e the reserve squads from India, Pakistan, Sri Lanka, Afghanistan, Bangladesh as well as 3 qualifiers from the 2024 ACC Men's Premier Cup.
[src:afghanistan-a-cricket-team/2024-acc-emerging-teams-asia-cup] Afghanistan A won the tournament, defeating Sri Lanka A by 7 wickets in the final.
[src:afghanistan-a-cricket-team/2024-acc-emerging-teams-asia-cup] The teams were placed in the following groups.
[src:afghanistan-a-cricket-team/2024-acc-emerging-teams-asia-cup] Afghanistan also named Bashir Ahmad, Hassan Eisakhil, Sediqullah Pacha and Mohammad Saleem as reserve players.
[src:afghanistan-a-cricket-team/2024-acc-emerging-teams-asia-cup] Before the start of the tournament, Afghanistan A played two warm-up matches against Oman A, followed by a T20 Tri-series involving hosts Oman A, Hong Kong and Afghanistan A.
[src:afghanistan-a-cricket-team/2024-acc-emerging-teams-asia-cup] The fixtures were announced by ACC on 20 September 2024.
[src:afghanistan-a-cricket-team/afghanistan-a-cricket-team] The **Afghanistan A cricket team** is a national cricket team representing Afghanistan.
[src:afghanistan-a-cricket-team/afghanistan-a-cricket-team] It is the 'second-tier' of international Afghan cricket, below the full Afghanistan national cricket team.
[src:afghanistan-a-cricket-team/afghanistan-a-cricket-team] Matches played by Afghanistan A are not considered to be One Day Internationals, instead receiving List A classification.
[src:afghanistan-a-cricket-team/afghanistan-a-cricket-team] Their first match was against the Tajikistan national cricket team in December 2013.
[src:afghanistan-a-cricket-team/afghanistan-a-cricket-team] In 2017, they played a five-match series against the Zimbabwe A cricket team in Zimbabwe.
[src:afghanistan-a-cricket-team/afghanistan-a-cricket-team] In July 2017, they were added to the South Africa A Team Tri-Series, after Australia A withdrew.
[src:afghanistan-a-cricket-team/afghanistan-a-cricket-team] They toured Bangladesh in July 2019, playing two first-class and five 50-over matches against Bangladesh A.
[src:afghanistan-a-cricket-team/afghanistan-a-cricket-team] In October 2024, the Afghanistan A team played in the ACC emerging team asia cup tournament where they won matches against Sri Lanka and Bangladesh A but lost against Honk Kong A.
[src:afghanistan-a-cricket-team/afghanistan-a-cricket-team] However they won against India A in the semi final by scoring the highest ever total in the tournament history of 206.
[src:afghanistan-a-cricket-team/afghanistan-a-cricket-team] 2024 ACC Emerging Teams Asia Cup final was played between Afghanistan A and Sri Lanka A Team on 27 October 2024 which Afghanistan A won and won their first title as such.
